    <h1>Lawvere Theories</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski · 2017 · <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2017/08/26/lawvere-theories/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 24</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-17/">🍞 Ch17 (Monads)</a>, <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-16/">🍞 Ch16 (Adjunctions)</a>. 12 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lawvere_theory"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Lawvere theory</a></strong> is a category whose objects are natural numbers (powers of a generic object) and whose morphisms are n-ary operations. A <strong>model</strong> is a product-preserving functor L &rarr; Set. Every algebraic structure (monoids, groups, rings) is a model of some Lawvere theory. Every finitary monad arises from a Lawvere theory, and every Lawvere theory induces a monad. Lawvere theories compose better than monads: they have coproducts and tensor products where monads have no generic composition recipe.</p>
    </div>

