    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>The blog post builds Lawvere theories in five steps: FinSet &rarr; its skeleton F &rarr; F<sup>op</sup> &rarr; the Lawvere theory L &rarr; models Mod(L, Set). This page collapses the first three steps and focuses on what the resulting category looks like (objects = arities, morphisms = operations). The coend formula T<sub>L</sub>(a) = &int;<sup>n</sup> a<sup>n</sup> &times; L(n, 1) is presented through the list monad example rather than in full generality. The blog post also discusses the category <strong>Law</strong> of Lawvere theories, where a morphism between theories is a product-preserving functor that commutes with the embedding from F<sup>op</sup>. We skip this level of abstraction. The key point preserved: Lawvere theories and finitary monads are equivalent descriptions of algebraic structure, but Lawvere theories compose (via coproducts and tensor products) where monads do not.</p>

